[30;1m1555 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m1556 | [0m[35m  L-BFGS is a quasi-Newton method that multiplies the update (gradient)[0m
[30;1m1557 | [0m[35m  with an approximation of the inverse Hessian. This algorithm does not need[0m
[30;1m1558 | [0m[35m  access to the Hessian, as this approximation is constructed from the gradient[0m
[30;1m1559 | [0m[35m  evaluations seen during optimization. L-BFGS is a limited-memory variant of[0m

[30;1m384 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m385 | [0m[35m  For each variable `var_k`, the coefficient is given by:[0m
[30;1m386 | [0m[35m    \sum_k cov(df/d var_k, d cv/d var_k) / (\sum var(d cv/d var_k) + eps)[0m

[30;1m338 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m339 | [0m[35m  # [E_{p(x; \theta)} \nabla_{\theta} h(x; \theta)[0m
[30;1m340 | [0m[35m  cv_param_grads = jax.grad(param_fn)(params)[0m
[30;1m341 | [0m[35m  # The gradients of the closed form expectation of the control variate[0m
[30;1m342 | [0m[35m  # with respect to the parameters: # \nabla_{\theta} E_{p(x; \theta)}].[0m

[30;1m153 | [0m[35m      initial  weights of  the model (or the parameter group), and g_0 is the[0m
[30;1m154 | [0m[35m      gradient of the first step.[0m

[30;1m134 | [0m[35m  r"""Distance over Gradients optimizer.[0m
[30;1m135 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m136 | [0m[35m  DoG updates parameters :math:`w_t` with stochastic gradients :math:`g_t` [0m

[30;1m59 | [0m[35m      initial  weights of  the model (or the parameter group), and g_0 is the[0m

[30;1m61 | [0m[35m      As discussed in the paper, this value should be small enough to ensure[0m

[30;1m63 | [0m[35m      diverge.[0m
